Question:
How many integer triples $(x,y,z)$ satisfy the following system of congruences:
\[
\begin{array}{rcl}
x - yz^2 &\equiv & 1 \pmod{13} \\
xz + y &\equiv & 4 \pmod{13}
\end{array}
\]
where $0 \leq x < 13$, $0 \leq y < 13$, and $0 \leq z < 13$?

Generated_answer:
The length of AB is 13 and the length of CD is 10. The perimeter of ABCD is the sum of the lengths of its sides. Since ABCD is a trapezoid, it has two parallel sides (AB and CD) and two non-parallel sides (AD and BC). The length of AD is equal to the length of CD, and the length of BC is equal to the length of AB. Therefore, the perimeter of ABCD is 13 + 10 + 10 + 13 = 46.​

Calculate the volume of the solid generated by rotating the region bounded by the curve {eq}y = \frac{1}{x}, \ x = 1, \ x = 3, \text{ and } y = 0 {/eq} about the line {eq}x = 3 {/eq} using the method of cylindrical shells. To find the volume of the solid, we apply the method of cylindrical shells. The region is bounded by {eq}y = \frac{1}{x} {/eq}, {eq}x = 1 {/eq}, {eq}x = 3 {/eq}, and {eq}y = 0 {/eq}. The radius of the cylindrical shell is the distance from the line {eq}x = 3 {/eq} to the curve, which is {eq}3 - x {/eq}. The height of the shell is the function value {eq}y = \frac{1}{x} {/eq}. The volume element {eq}dV {/eq} is given by {eq}2\pi r h dx {/eq}, where {eq}r {/eq} is the radius and {eq}h {/eq} is the height.

Thus, the volume {eq}V {/eq} is:

{eq}\begin{align*}
V &= \int_{1}^{3} 2\pi (3 - x) \left(\frac{1}{x}\right) dx \\
&= 2\pi \int_{1}^{3} \left(\frac{3}{x} - 1\right) dx \\
&= 2\pi \left[3\ln|x| - x\right]_{1}^{3} \\
&= 2\pi \left[(3\ln(3) - 3) - (3\ln(1) - 1)\right] \\
&= 2\pi \left[3\ln(3) - 2\right] \\
&\approx 9.36 \text{ cubic units}
\end{align*}

{/eq}

Let $A$ be a square matrix of rank $1$. Then, there exists a vector $v$ such that $A = vv^T$. The minimal polynomial of $A$ is the monic polynomial of least degree that annihilates $A$. Since $A^2 = (vv^T)^2 = v(v^Tv)v^T = (v^Tv)A$, we have $A^2 - (v^Tv)A = 0$. Therefore, the minimal polynomial of $A$ is $x^2 - (v^Tv)x$.
